    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i guess i've heard people say stuff about insects or something getting in there. is it usually just bugs or is there anything else that actually causes these blockages during a flight?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Bugs are certainly a common culprit, especially when flying through dense, humid air, but you can't rule out other things either. Icing is a major concern, especially at higher altitudes or in freezing conditions, as ice buildup can completely obstruct the opening. Sometimes, foreign object debris (FOD) from dust, sand, or even tiny pieces of bird droppings can get lodged in the tube. It's a real hazard, and it's why pilots are constantly reminded to check those tubes before takeoff.",
